## 💾 Step 1: Create a GitHub Account

1. Go to the official website:
   👉 https://github.com/
2. Click **Sign up**
3. Create your account (username, email, password)
4. Verify your email

✅ Your GitHub account is now ready.

---

## 💻 Step 2: Install Git (REQUIRED)

Git must be installed on your computer.

### 🔹 Download Git
Official website:

👉 https://git-scm.com/downloads

Choose your operating system and download.

---

### 🔹 Install Git (Windows)
During installation:
- Use default options
- Choose **Git from the command line and also from 3rd-party software**
- Keep default editor (you can change later)

Finish installation.

---

### 🔹 Verify Git Installation

Open **Command Prompt** or **PowerShell** and type:

```bash
git --version

If you see a version number → ✅ Git is installed correctly.

---

Step 3: Connect GitHub to Your Computer
🔹 Configure Git (First Time Only)

Run these commands (replace with your info):

git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your@email.com"


This information will appear in your commits.

---

🧩 Using GitHub with Visual Studio Code

VS Code has built-in Git support.

🔹 Check Git in VS Code

Open VS Code

Open a folder

Click Source Control icon (left sidebar)

If Git is installed, VS Code will detect it automatically.

---

📂 Creating Your First Git Repository

Option 1: From GitHub Website

-Go to GitHub

-Click New repository

-Name it (example):Learning_Python_2025
-Add a README

-Click Create repository

---

Option 2: Clone Repository to Your Computer

In VS Code terminal:

git clone https://github.com/USERNAME/REPOSITORY_NAME.git

Example:

git clone https://github.com/Peymanmxli-stack/Learning_Python_2025.git

🔄 Basic Git Commands (Beginner) 

Command	                        Description
git status	                 Check file changes
git add .	                   Stage all changes
git commit -m "message"	       Save changes
git push	                    Upload to GitHub
git pull	                     Download updates

Example workflow:

git add .
git commit -m "Add new module"
git push

❌ Common Beginner Mistakes

-❌ Git not installed

-❌ Not logged into GitHub

-❌ Forgetting to commit

-❌ Forgetting to push changes

-❌ Editing files outside repository folder

---

✅ What You Should Know Before Moving On

Before continuing, you should:

✔️ Have a GitHub account

✔️ Have Git installed

✔️ Clone a repository

✔️ Push code to GitHub

Once completed, you are ready to manage your projects professionally 🚀

